F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/upetoffen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Petoffen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/11/02 3:08:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980rants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=916.topic&index=14>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/craig234/eq/petportrait.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: fdhfdhfg</span><hr size=1> Krozar, the points not mentioned are that it's in Netflix's interest for the ads to be as effective as possible; and that if popup killers ruin popup ads, there won't be any money in them and they'll go away.<br>
<br>
During the period that popup killers are available but not widely used, you have a bit of a 'sweet spot' that you can use the web site for free, with no popups with the ad killer, while others pay for the site through spending money with the sponsor. I'll leave the question whether it's right or not aside for now.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with the complaints about some ads, but the more effective place to voice them would be with the advertiser. Drop Netflix a note saying their ads make you determined not to be a customer and the reason; might help or not, but it's the more effective thing to do.<br>
<br>
And while complaints are fine, people shouldn't carry them too far such that they're in disagreement with the basic premise of ad-sponsored sites, that ultimately they're paid for by the site users responding to sponsors. If anything, if you like a site, give extra preference to responding to its ads (unless you object to them for some reason).<br>
<br>
It's the lack of effectiveness of web advertising that has killed many sites, like gamepower.com and gamecenter.com and pushed others to pay systems, like Allakhazams and EQprices and either eqatlas or eqmaps.<br>
<br>
So we aren't disagreeing too much on this... <p>Arch Mage 60, Master of the epic elemental magics, collector of robes<BR>
